27
0:1:18,67 --> 0:1:22,267
(Matt Olien, narrator)
If you've driven by farm fields
in the Upper Great Plains,


28
0:1:22,267 --> 0:1:24,367
you've no doubt noticed
patches of white,


29
0:1:24,367 --> 0:1:26,501
chalky soil,
usually near roads and ditches,


30
0:1:26,501 --> 0:1:28,434
that just doesn't
seem to belong,


31
0:1:28,434 --> 0:1:30,33
and doesn't seem to go away.


32
0:1:30,33 --> 0:1:31,701
Farmers wish it would.


33
0:1:31,701 --> 0:1:34,234
It's soil salinity,
too much salt in the soil,


34
0:1:34,234 --> 0:1:35,901
and it can prove
nearly impossible


35
0:1:35,901 --> 0:1:38,334
to grow a productive crop
in those areas.


36
0:1:38,334 --> 0:1:42,0
Overall reduced soil health,
so compaction issues,


37
0:1:42,0 --> 0:1:44,367
reduced biological activity.


38
0:1:44,367 --> 0:1:46,567
You don't have
as good of soil to till.


39
0:1:46,567 --> 0:1:48,234
It's harder to work the soil.


40
0:1:48,234 --> 0:1:50,267
A lot of that depends on your
strategies


41
0:1:50,267 --> 0:1:52,67
you're using for management--
if you're using


42
0:1:52,67 --> 0:1:54,67
conventional tillage
or no till or strip till.


43
0:1:54,67 --> 0:1:55,934
But it really depends
on the producer


44
0:1:55,934 --> 0:1:57,534
and what they're willing to try.


45
0:1:57,534 --> 0:2:0,133
In my area I would say


46
0:2:0,133 --> 0:2:3,67
over 95% of my fields have
salinity,


47
0:2:3,67 --> 0:2:5,567
and 80% of them have
visible white spots


48
0:2:5,567 --> 0:2:7,467
