49
0:2:7,467 --> 0:2:10,33
All of my producers
are very concerned about it


50
0:2:10,33 --> 0:2:13,167
and are actively looking for
answers and trying new things


51
0:2:13,167 --> 0:2:15,2
and trying to seed
some cover crops,


52
0:2:15,2 --> 0:2:17,734
trying some crop rotations,
trying some limited drainage


53
0:2:17,734 --> 0:2:19,501
when they can get
the permission.


54
0:2:19,501 --> 0:2:22,634
So the producer is going
to try to pick the crop


55
0:2:22,634 --> 0:2:25,2
that gives him the best option
and economic return.


56
0:2:25,2 --> 0:2:27,234
(narrator)
Excess Salinity
is caused generally


57
0:2:27,234 --> 0:2:30,868
by too wet of conditions
resulting in a high water table.


58
0:2:30,868 --> 0:2:33,467
Most agree the problem
in the Upper Great Plains


59
0:2:33,467 --> 0:2:35,1
got worse around 1993


60
0:2:35,1 --> 0:2:38,968
when the dry cycle converted to
a wet cycle and has never left.


61
0:2:38,968 --> 0:2:42,901
But the problem has been around
for centuries.


62
0:2:42,901 --> 0:2:47,267
(Dr. Jaradat) The land
in Mesopotamia is very flat,


63
0:2:47,267 --> 0:2:50,67
and irrigating that land
created problems


64
0:2:50,67 --> 0:2:53,367
in addition to the high
temperature


65
0:2:53,367 --> 0:2:56,968
and high evaporation from
the irrigated water.


66
0:2:56,968 --> 0:3:0,834
Salts became concentrated,
and the irrigation water


67
0:3:0,834 --> 0:3:5,667
coming from the twin rivers,
the Tigris and Euphrates,


68
0:3:5,667 --> 0:3:9,968
enriched that salt
in the Mesopotamia plain,


69
0:3:9,968 --> 0:3:12,868
and in less than 1500 years,


70
0:3:12,868 --> 0:3:15,234
the problems started showing up


71
0:3:15,234 --> 0:3:18,601
to the point that
most fertile parts


72
0:3:18,601 --> 0:3:21,934
of lower Mesopotamia
turned into white crusts.


73
0:3:21,934 --> 0:3:24,567
People went hungry,
and cities


74
0:3:24,567 --> 0:3:27,334
and the empires themselves
crumbled


75
0:3:27,334 --> 0:3:31,33
because of the loss
of their wealth.


76
0:3:31,33 --> 0:3:32,801
(Dr. Cihacek) This is a geologic
process


77
0:3:32,801 --> 0:3:35,567
so it's been going on for a long
period of time.


78
0:3:35,567 --> 0:3:37,234
We've got relatively young
glacial soil.


79
0:3:37,234 --> 0:3:40,334
A lot of our soils were pushed
in here by the glaciers,


80
0:3:40,334 --> 0:3:41,934
spread out on the landscape.


81
0:3:41,934 --> 0:3:44,968
So as these salts weather--
they're young materials;


82
0:3:44,968 --> 0:3:48,434
there's a lot of things
to weather in there.


83
0:3:48,434 --> 0:3:51,33
They dissolve
and go into the water.


84
0:3:51,33 --> 0:3:55,334
Then wherever the water goes,
they carry these salt minerals.


85
0:3:55,334 --> 0:3:58,1
(Dr. Abdullah) Although it is
a problem here,


86
0:3:58,1 --> 0:3:59,667
but it's no comparison


87
0:3:59,667 --> 0:4:3,267
to the salinity problem in other
parts of the world.


88
0:4:3,267 --> 0:4:5,767
Just to give you
an example-- California,


89
0:4:5,767 --> 0:4:8,234
the Joaquin Valley
and the Salton Sea.


90
0:4:8,234 --> 0:4:10,434
The problems there are
much bigger.


91
0:4:10,434 --> 0:4:13,133
The world is losing
approximately


92
0:4:13,133 --> 0:4:17,33
a million hectares a year
to salinity,


93
0:4:17,33 --> 0:4:21,2
and there are 200 million
hectares of saline land


94
0:4:21,2 --> 0:4:25,434
which is not producing up
to its productive capacity.


95
0:4:25,434 --> 0:4:28,1
There are issues
in the Nile Delta


96
0:4:28,1 --> 0:4:31,3
especially after the
construction of the Aswan Dam.


97
0:4:31,3 --> 0:4:33,968
After the construction
of the dam,


98
0:4:33,968 --> 0:4:37,133
this kind of natural remedy,
so to speak,


99
0:4:37,133 --> 0:4:44,3
of soil fertility and handling
salinity stopped abruptly.


100
0:4:44,3 --> 0:4:51,467
Based on that, in fact, major
health problems were created.


101
0:4:51,467 --> 0:4:54,701
(narrator)
In our region,
the topography of the land


102
0:4:54,701 --> 0:4:56,767
has lent itself
to salinity problems,


103
0:4:56,767 --> 0:4:59,1
forcing many farmers
to move this land


104
0:4:59,1 --> 0:5:0,834
to the Conservation Reserve
Program.


105
0:5:0,834 --> 0:5:2,701
When the glaciers came
through here,


106
0:5:2,701 --> 0:5:4,601
they ground up to pure shale,


107
0:5:4,601 --> 0:5:8,1
and most of the salinity
that is in our soil


108
0:5:8,1 --> 0:5:9,968
originated
from the pure shale formation


109
0:5:9,968 --> 0:5:12,0
in Eastern North Dakota
at least.


110
0:5:12,0 --> 0:5:14,501
We were just looking
in our training yesterday


111
0:5:14,501 --> 0:5:16,868
at a soil survey
that was completed


112
0:5:16,868 --> 0:5:19,2
in Stutsman County
back in the '80's


113
0:5:19,2 --> 0:5:21,67
before the wet cycle
really started.


114
0:5:21,67 --> 0:5:23,601
There was only,
I think, about 10 acres


115
0:5:23,601 --> 0:5:26,434
of a whole quarter section
that was mapped saline.


116
0:5:26,434 --> 0:5:28,634
I believe that there's
no question


117
0:5:28,634 --> 0:5:31,968
but that some of the salinity
that we're seeing


118
0:5:31,968 --> 0:5:35,234
and the degree and the nature
of the salinity,


119
0:5:35,234 --> 0:5:37,567
it's a function of what we're
doing with water.


120
0:5:37,567 --> 0:5:39,601
It's linked to
the Red River Valley floods.


121
0:5:39,601 --> 0:5:41,267
It's linked to overland flow.


122
0:5:41,267 --> 0:5:42,934
So consequently
what that means is,


123
0:5:42,934 --> 0:5:45,367
is that there's simply
more water on the landscape.


124
0:5:45,367 --> 0:5:48,67
More water either
runs off the landscape.


125
0:5:48,67 --> 0:5:51,2
More water resides within
the landscape, and there's


126
0:5:51,2 --> 0:5:54,734
less water that is moved back
up through evapotranspiration.


127
0:5:54,734 --> 0:5:56,501



128
0:5:56,501 --> 0:5:59,501
It's roughly 10.8


129
0:5:59,501 --> 0:6:2,167
deciSiemens per meter.


130
0:6:2,167 --> 0:6:5,367
And in this type of sampling,


131
0:6:5,367 --> 0:6:7,634
it'll show less salts
'cause we have


132
0:6:7,634 --> 0:6:11,1
a higher concentration of water
with this soil, but that would


133
0:6:11,1 --> 0:6:14,0
easily equate to 25 deciSiemens
on the other methods,


134
0:6:14,0 --> 0:6:17,634
and that is restrictive
to almost all plant growth.


135
0:6:17,634 --> 0:6:20,133
(narrator)
Salinity can be
invisible or visible.


136
0:6:20,133 --> 0:6:23,601
Either way, it is affecting
the bottom line and livelihood


137
0:6:23,601 --> 0:6:26,4
of producers all over
the Upper Great Plains.


138
0:6:26,4 --> 0:6:29,234
Joleen Hadrich with
North Dakota State University


139
0:6:29,234 --> 0:6:31,734
has researched
the economic impact of salinity.


140
0:6:31,734 --> 0:6:35,4
What we know is that their yield
is going to decrease,


141
0:6:35,4 --> 0:6:38,0
and that, of course, is going to
relate


142
0:6:38,0 --> 0:6:40,734
into lower revenues and a lower
profit level.


143
0:6:40,734 --> 0:6:44,467
Slightly saline would result
in about a 15% yield loss.


144
0:6:44,467 --> 0:6:47,33
The moderate
would be 50% yield loss.


145
0:6:47,33 --> 0:6:50,3
When I applied
the average crop prices


146
0:6:50,3 --> 0:6:54,567
that we're receiving right now
in those yield decreases,


147
0:6:54,567 --> 0:6:58,367
it resulted in $150 million
decrease in revenue.


148
0:6:58,367 --> 0:7:2,1
(Bill Schuh)
I think it's first
and foremost a crop problem


149
0:7:2,1 --> 0:7:3,801
and secondly
an economic problem.


150
0:7:3,801 --> 0:7:7,701
The loss of crop yields from
salinization of the soil


151
0:7:7,701 --> 0:7:11,534
is a very, very major economic
loss for our state.


152
0:7:11,534 --> 0:7:14,267
(Joe Breker) I did a recent poll


153
0:7:14,267 --> 0:7:17,901
with our group, our corn growers
group, and it was


154
0:7:17,901 --> 0:7:22,33
fairly common to have producers
from all over the state


155
0:7:22,33 --> 0:7:27,167
that are in the corn growers
that had from 10% to 15%


156
0:7:27,167 --> 0:7:31,0
of their farms
severely impacted by salinity.


157
0:7:31,0 --> 0:7:36,234
In terms of an overall problem,
we could say


158
0:7:36,234 --> 0:7:39,467
that the agricultural land
in Canada,


159
0:7:39,467 --> 0:7:42,234
about 1/3 includes
salt-affected soils.


160
0:7:42,234 --> 0:7:46,968
If I'm a producer,
I will try to minimize that--


161
0:7:46,968 --> 0:7:50,868
any kind of problems
that relate to salinity--


162
0:7:50,868 --> 0:7:53,334
primarily
because my assessed lands,


163
0:7:53,334 --> 0:7:55,968
the assessments, will decrease


164
0:7:55,968 --> 0:7:59,801
if my lands are
identified as salinized.


165
0:7:59,801 --> 0:8:4,567
When we get to an EC of about
8 which is moderately saline,


166
0:8:4,567 --> 0:8:8,33
we have at least 50% reduction
in yields on wheat.


167
0:8:8,33 --> 0:8:11,434
You can have 75% yield loss
on corn,


168
0:8:11,434 --> 0:8:14,133
and soybeans, you might as well
forget it


169
0:8:14,133 --> 0:8:17,834
because we're down to maybe 10%
or not even worth harvesting.


170
0:8:17,834 --> 0:8:19,467
Basically it's an osmotic
problem.


171
0:8:19,467 --> 0:8:22,0
If you get too much salt on
the outside,


172
0:8:22,0 --> 0:8:24,467
you have too much osmotic
suction on the outside,


173
0:8:24,467 --> 0:8:26,801
it competes with the electrolyte
in the plant,


174
0:8:26,801 --> 0:8:29,33
and the plant reaches a point


175
0:8:29,33 --> 0:8:31,0
where it can't imbibe water
properly,


176
0:8:31,0 --> 0:8:32,901
and you start getting yield
reductions.


177
0:8:32,901 --> 0:8:35,67
(narrator) Another fear is
what has happened


178
0:8:35,67 --> 0:8:37,0
in other parts of the world.--


179
0:8:37,0 --> 0:8:39,701
health issues, food supply
issues and water quality issues.


180
0:8:39,701 --> 0:8:44,2
We constantly review the best
available science from EPA


181
0:8:44,2 --> 0:8:47,767
and their contractors that they
work with--universities


182
0:8:47,767 --> 0:8:50,767
that develop the best
toxicological information


183
0:8:50,767 --> 0:8:54,868
that's available to date,
and we incorporate those.


184
0:8:54,868 --> 0:8:58,2
If it's something immediate,
we do it right away


185
0:8:58,2 --> 0:9:0,234
in our water quality standard.


186
0:9:0,234 --> 0:9:4,0
(Bill Schuh) I don't think that
on the basis


187
0:9:4,0 --> 0:9:7,4
of current EPA and CDC documents
we can conclude


188
0:9:7,4 --> 0:9:10,367
that sulphate is particularly
damaging to water quality.


189
0:9:10,367 --> 0:9:12,634
As far as drinking water quality
is concerned,


190
0:9:12,634 --> 0:9:15,868
people drink water that have
a lot of salts in them.


191
0:9:15,868 --> 0:9:18,534
There's a very wide range
of qualities in the waters


192
0:9:18,534 --> 0:9:20,834
that people drink
and are capable of drinking.


193
0:9:20,834 --> 0:9:23,968
Right here in this area of the
field--this is one of


194
0:9:23,968 --> 0:9:26,267
the more obvious places that
you'll see salt.


195
0:9:26,267 --> 0:9:29,267
The obvious effects of the salt
is this white crusting.


196
0:9:29,267 --> 0:9:32,267
I see too many guys trying
to manage their salinity.


197
0:9:32,267 --> 0:9:36,0
They put some into CRP,
but they don't go far enough,


198
0:9:36,0 --> 0:9:38,734
and then that salinity just
continues to move out,


199
0:9:38,734 --> 0:9:42,0
and then they're mad because
they don't have an impact,


200
0:9:42,0 --> 0:9:44,501
and it's just making it worse
and worse.


201
0:9:44,501 --> 0:9:48,67
(narrator)
And as you'll see next, the
solutions farmers come up with


202
0:9:48,67 --> 0:9:49,667
can mean the difference


203
0:9:49,667 --> 0:9:51,467
between lost revenue
and successful yields.


204
0:9:51,467 --> 0:9:55,467



205
0:9:55,467 --> 0:9:59,133
Good management practices
for salinity would include


206
0:9:59,133 --> 0:10:1,2
definitely
CRP, understanding that,


207
0:10:1,2 --> 0:10:3,434
the variable rate and
site specific technologies


208
0:10:3,434 --> 0:10:6,0
is the biggest one
that I'm involved with.


209
0:10:6,0 --> 0:10:8,534
(David Burkland)
Actually in Grand Forks
County here,


210
0:10:8,534 --> 0:10:10,2
the level of salinity is


211
0:10:10,2 --> 0:10:13,67
one of the higher levels
in the Red River Valley


212
0:10:13,67 --> 0:10:15,267
so we've tried
a lot of different things.


213
0:10:15,267 --> 0:10:17,868
We have put some land
into CRP,


214
0:10:17,868 --> 0:10:19,934
but we've done other things too


215
0:10:19,934 --> 0:10:23,234
to try to overcome the saline
conditions--just crop choice


216
0:10:23,234 --> 0:10:25,968
is a big factor,
picking the right crops.


217
0:10:25,968 --> 0:10:29,3
Picking crops that are tolerant
to saline conditions


218
0:10:29,3 --> 0:10:31,334
is real important.


219
0:10:31,334 --> 0:10:34,2
(Shawn Kasprick)
On the precision ag side
of things,


220
0:10:34,2 --> 0:10:35,901
we got different
site-specific products


221
0:10:35,901 --> 0:10:39,33
and services that we can provide
that will give the growers


222
0:10:39,33 --> 0:10:41,1
a handle on
where their salinity is,


223
0:10:41,1 --> 0:10:44,267
what impact it has
on their crop, and how far out


224
0:10:44,267 --> 0:10:46,4
that impact really is
effecting their crop.


225
0:10:46,4 --> 0:10:48,801
That all will wrap up eventually


226
0:10:48,801 --> 0:10:51,501
into a variable rate
application for fertility


227
0:10:51,501 --> 0:10:53,834
and eventually
the grower's bottom line.


228
0:10:53,834 --> 0:10:58,4
(Joe Michels)
It takes a little while to get
established.


229
0:10:58,4 --> 0:11:1,2
It did the job for me.


230
0:11:1,2 --> 0:11:3,534
We have had salinity issues.


231
0:11:3,534 --> 0:11:9,67
There's one hayfield we got
from a fella that got sick.


232
0:11:9,67 --> 0:11:11,434
He told
the landlord that he


233
0:11:11,434 --> 0:11:14,133
wanted to
rent it to my dad


234
0:11:14,133 --> 0:11:16,2
back in
the early 70's.


235
0:11:16,2 --> 0:11:20,467
We took it over;
the ground was white.


236
0:11:20,467 --> 0:11:26,434
It would grow foxtail, kochia,
and not too good at that.


237
0:11:26,434 --> 0:11:28,567
Then the garrison
seemed to help.


238
0:11:28,567 --> 0:11:33,868
It took a long time to
establish, but it is very thick.


239
0:11:33,868 --> 0:11:35,834
We got a good root structure


240
0:11:35,834 --> 0:11:38,901
where Dad could drive
across there with a swather


241
0:11:38,901 --> 0:11:41,367
in the water and not get stuck.


242
0:11:41,367 --> 0:11:44,3
(Dr. Cihacek)
Cover crops, especially
deep-rooted cover crops,


243
0:11:44,3 --> 0:11:48,667
